To serve a JSON object instead of a string, you can modify the "hello_world()" function to return a JSON response using the Flask "jsonify" function. Here's an example of how to modify the previous code to serve a JSON object:

```
from flask import Flask, jsonify

app = Flask(name)

@app.route('/')
def hello_world():
data = {
'message': 'Hello, world!'
}
return jsonify(data)

if name == 'main':
app.run()
```

In this updated version of the code, we import the "jsonify" function from Flask and use it to create a JSON response. We define a dictionary called "data" that contains a single key-value pair, where the key is "message" and the value is "Hello, world!".

The "jsonify" function takes a dictionary as its argument and returns a JSON-formatted response with the appropriate content-type headers. When we visit the root URL of our Flask application, we will see a JSON object with the "message" key and its associated value.

You can test this modified script in the same way as the previous example, by opening a web browser and navigating to http://localhost:5000/. This time, you should see a JSON object with the "message" key and its associated value displayed in your browser.

To serve a JSON object instead of a string, you can modify the hello_world function to return a dictionary object instead of a string, and use Flask's jsonify method to convert the dictionary to JSON format. Here's an updated example:

